[{"id":"VR597537","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Two figures are shown, labeled Figure 1 and Figure 2 respectively. In each figure, two spheres are shown and arranged horizontally. The left sphere is labeled sphere X and is large and shaded darkly. The right sphere is labeled sphere Y and is small and shaded lightly. In Figure 1, the distance between the two spheres is 3 d. In Figure 2, the distance between the two spheres is d. A note indicates that the figures are not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR597537.g04.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Nonconducting Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span> is fixed in place and has a charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive uppercase Q\"><math alttext=\"positive uppercase Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Conducting Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is electrically neutral and starts at a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3 d\"><math alttext=\"3 d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> away from Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>, as indicated in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>I</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> above. Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is then brought toward Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span> to a new position <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> away from Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>, as indicated in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>II</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> above. Which of the following is true of the electric force on Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> from Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span> and the electric potential energy of the two-sphere system as Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is brought toward Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span> ?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR597537_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric force on <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is attractive and the electric potential energy decreases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric force on <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is attractive and the electric potential energy increases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric force on <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is repulsive and the electric potential energy decreases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric force on <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is repulsive and the electric potential energy increases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The electric force on <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span> is nonexistent and the electric potential energy remains the same.</p>"],"answer":0}]